affiliation={Faculty of Computer and Mathematical Sciences, Universiti Teknologi MARA (UiTM), Shah Alam, 40450, Malaysia; Department of Architecture and Built Environment, The University of Nottingham, University Park, Nottingham, NG7 2RD, United Kingdom},
abstract={Accurate identification of paddy leaf diseases is vital for timely intervention and sustainable rice production. This study proposes a novel, fully R-based deep learning framework for paddy leaf disease classification that integrates model performance evaluation, statistical testing, and post hoc explainability. The methodology incorporates four CNN architectures-Baseline CNN, ResNet50, DenseNet121, InceptionV3-and a novel Hybrid CNN that performs deep feature-level fusion across all models. All networks were trained using a curated dataset comprising six paddy disease categories, with extensive data augmentation applied to enhance generalization. The dataset consisted of 6000 images, split into 4800 for training and 1200 for validation across all classes. A structured hyperparameter optimization strategy was implemented using the tfruns package, and all models were benchmarked using confusion matrix-derived metrics. The Hybrid CNN – Simple Ensemble achieved the best overall performance, recording a mean accuracy of 0.821 and a mean Macro-F1 of 0.818, thereby surpassing the best single model (DenseNet121 Fine-tuned, accuracy 0.793). Statistical validation using McNemar’s test confirmed that the Hybrid Simple Ensemble’s predictions differed significantly from those of other models. At the same time, Cohen’s Kappa analysis indicated only moderate agreement with DenseNet121 and weaker agreement with InceptionV3 and ResNet50. To ensure transparency, explainable AI (XAI) techniques-such as SHAP, LIME, and Grad-CAM-were employed to visualize and quantify model attention. Results demonstrated that the Hybrid Simple Ensemble consistently focused on biologically meaningful lesion and streak regions, with higher faithfulness scores than DenseNet121, thereby enhancing both predictive accuracy and interpretability. This study presents a reproducible and interpretable deep learning pipeline for agricultural diagnostics, demonstrating the viability of R for end-to-end CNN development. The inclusion of a hybrid CNN ensemble strategy, coupled with integrated SHAP, LIME, and Grad-CAM explanations, establishes a stronger foundation for deployable, trust-aware plant disease detection systems. © 2025 Elsevier Ltd. All rights are reserved, including those for text and data mining, AI training, and similar technologies.},
